node.text:
For the Academy Award-winning costume designer Ruth E. Carter, a project starts with research. “I read that script, I go on that journey. I immerse myself in the story,” she said.

Ruth, who’s known for her work on films including “Do the Right Thing,” “Malcolm X” and "Dolemite Is My Name," won an Oscar for her visionary work on “Black Panther.” But for her, success is about more than awards: “Winning is seeing your vision come to fruition,” she said. “That's winning.” 

We spent a day with Ruth, a member of our #BlackDesignVisionaries grant committee. Watch to hear about Spike Lee’s mentorship, her interview for “Black Panther” and more. #ShareBlackStories

The @nba. @carnegiehall. @nytmag. These are just a few of the household names Bobby C. Martin Jr. has worked with to create enduring branding and visual identity systems. “Redesigning an American institution is absolutely terrifying,” said Bobby, co-founder of the New York branding and design agency @championsdesign. “But it’s also thrilling.”

We spent a day with Bobby, a member of our #BlackDesignVisionaries grant committee, at his East Village studio. Watch to hear about his visionary approach to graphic design. #ShareBlackStories

For the Academy Award-winning costume designer Ruth E. Carter, a project starts with research. “I read that script, I go on that journey. I immerse myself in the story,” she said.

Ruth, who’s known for her work on films including “Do the Right Thing,” “Malcolm X” and "Dolemite Is My Name," won an Oscar for her visionary work on “Black Panther.” But for her, success is about more than awards: “Winning is seeing your vision come to fruition,” she said. “That's winning.” 

We spent a day with Ruth, a member of our #BlackDesignVisionaries grant committee. Watch to hear about Spike Lee’s mentorship, her interview for “Black Panther” and more. #ShareBlackStories

#DesigninMotion ✨ “People get satisfied watching squishy things,” said @NikePurwitasarii, a designer from Jakarta, Indonesia. They want to watch “again and again” she added.

This animation is named after Blobby, a Jell-O-like creature from the animated series 𝐻𝑜𝑡𝑒𝑙 𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑦𝑙𝑣𝑎𝑛𝑖𝑎. But Disney movies initially inspired Nike to work in 3D animation. Through countless YouTube tutorials; lessons from her boyfriend, @divacndr, a motion designer; and trial and error, Nike has developed a style centered on cute, satisfying and colorful objects.  With each animation, Nike "tries so many times, until it looks just like the idea in my head." 💭

Note: This work was inspired by a piece by @vincentschwenk and @vitalygrossmann, which was posted on @vincentschwenk’s account in 2020.

#TheWorldNeedsMoreSpiralStaircases 🌀 When the avid architectural photographer @gabrielezocchi visited a friend in Zürich, Switzerland, he asked to see this marvel in the Altstetten neighborhood. Gabriele was in awe of the natural light leaking into the space, thanks to the steel wires circulating the inner core of the stairwell, creating a transparent effect. But the real “touch of magic” came when he stood directly beneath the stairs and looked up to see the spherical pendant lights, which reminded him of lava lamps — and gave the illusion of a much larger space. 🌋

node.text: #SundayShelfie 📚 Although the @rijksmuseum in Amsterdam is world-famous, the Cuypers library nestled inside could “easily be missed if you didn’t know it was there,” said @whatshotblog, who captured this breathtaking space. Laura, a book lover from London, England, was amazed at every design detail: the spiral staircase connecting rows upon rows of historical art books, the balconies that encircle the central space, and the amount of light coming in through the arched windows and vaulted-glass ceiling. “Usually old libraries are very dark,” Laura said. “But not here.” ✨

#DesignInMotion 🟦 “A beautiful mess.” That’s how @canalesbr1 (Bruno Canales), a creative director in Austin, Texas, describes his design process. “Sometimes I start with a piece of code. At other times I just write something in a notebook.” To create this piece, Bruno, who runs the design lab @crea.st, first developed the code. He tested different shapes and colors until he landed on something he liked.

“With a lot of my work, the story behind it is the process itself: the inspiration, the exploration, the merging of digital and surreal and, above all, the joy of playing with a set of tools with no real objective other than to express, investigate and reflect.” 🖥

#FromWhereWeDesign ✍🏽Every day, blind and low vision members of the Instagram community use assistive technology to discover and make connections. As part of our focus on accessibility, we’re working to give all community members the experience of swiping through their feeds quickly. These improvements are grounded in simplicity. While it once took as many as 30 swipes to experience a single post using assistive technology, users can now swipe from one post to the next in seconds — much simpler, and more efficient. ✨ It's all part of our ongoing effort to create a well-crafted Instagram experience that works for everyone, everywhere. See more in stories and on @facebookdesign!

Alt text: A video demonstrates how assistive technology used to scroll through an Instagram post, followed by a demonstration of a new, simpler process.

#FrameYourWorld 🌎 When designing @slowboat_atelier, a seaside cafe on Jeju Island in South Korea, the owner, HanJun Kim, kept his favorite camera in mind: the @Hasselblad XPan. “I was inspired by the panorama frame,” he said. “In this case, the window acts as the camera lens and the eyes of the customers are the film.” 🎞

In addition to the picture window, every detail in the cafe was carefully considered — including vintage furniture pieces, exposed concrete walls and high ceilings. “I remember reading an article saying that the higher the ceiling, the greater your creativity,” HanJun said. “I consider this place a café, but also a studio for reading and writing.” 📖

#ItsSaunaDay 🧖‍♀️ Take a deep breath, and imagine yourself stepping into this seaside sauna by @beebeskidmore. An Oregon duo known for their creative reinterpretations of architecture, Heidi Beebe and Doug Skidmore are no strangers to saunas. But this was their first freestanding design: a wood-frame building set atop a hand-poured concrete foundation, designed to fit seamlessly into the landscape, like a rock in a garden. Unlike most saunas, this one is inverted: Visitors step down to enter the cedar space, and descend the steps toward the picture window. Swipe to see the sauna’s sloped living roof, designed in consultation with the landscape firm Coyote Gardens, and visible to the residents from their deck. In Heidi’s words, “We wanted the roof to be beautiful from that perspective, and blend into the forest floor.” 🌱
